trie Case Files -- t12. Problematic Bodies and Agency: Women Patients in Canada, 1900-1950 -- tPart Five. 'Problem' Families: Arenas of Conflict, Targets of Reform -- t13. Uncovering and Reconstructing Family Violence: Ontario Criminal Case Files -- t14. Parents, Daughters, and Family Court Intrusions into Working-Class Life -- t15. The 'Grab Bag' Mennonite Refugee Family in Post-War Canada -- tAfterword. Telling Stories about Dead People -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCase files, records from all kinds of social, medical, governmental, military, and other agencies, become available to researchers once confidentiality is no longer in question. Such records are an important source for scholars in social history and related fields, providing insight not only into the lives of ordinary people but into the workings of the agencies that kept the records as well. Case files contain a wealth of information and challenge researchers by their complexity and the variety of approaches and methodologies their analysis demands. On the Case is a timely book intended to provide a forum for discussing the theoretical and methodological issues that case files raise. The book brings together theoretical debates, new research, and new research methods and offers compelling illustrations of the drama, conflict, and power relations that the case file can capture. This collection of essays features some of Canada's leading social historians. Readers will encounter an impressive array of case files, including psychiatrists' accounts of sexual deviants, employment records of sailors, state welfare and Indian Affairs reports, court records, the patient forms of hospital and asylum doctors, and state security files. While the contributors differ in choice of subject and approach, they share a commitment to the progressive traditions of social history. They recover the voices and actions of people - not only of those with power but also of those who seemingly have none.Case files have proved crucial to scholars developing such new fields of historical study as sexuality, gay and lesbian lives, and domestic violence, and have reinvigorated work in more established fields of history such as immigration, security and intelligence, and the modern welfare state. On the Case is unique in offering new research as well as guiding readers through recent debates and the various theoretical and methodological challenges created by case files.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHistorical sociologyxMethodology. 0aRecordszCanada. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh1 aBradbury, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrownlie, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCour, Lykke De La, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubinsky, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEpp, Marlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolz, Annalee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIacovetta, Franca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIacovetta, Franca, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKealey, Gregory S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittle, Margaret Hillyard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarks, Lynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaynard, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLaren, Angus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchinson, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/